<Node id="1"/>AUSTRALIA: Australian scientists cut solar energy costs.<Node id="57"/>
<Node id="58"/>Australian scientists cut solar energy costs.<Node id="103"/>
<Node id="104"/>Maria Moscaritolo<Node id="121"/>
<Node id="122"/>CANBERRA 1997-08-19<Node id="141"/>
<Node id="142"/>
<Node id="143"/>Australian scientists said on Tuesday they had developed a revolutionary process that could halve the costs of solar energy cells and bring cheap, clean power to the country's outback.<Node id="327"/>
<Node id="328"/>Scientist Andrew Blakers told Reuters the new cheaper cells could be in production within three years, offering a viable alternative to diesel generators in remote Australian areas and communities in small developing nations.<Node id="553"/>
<Node id="554"/>"We are still very much in the research and development phase," said Blakers, of the engineering and information technology faculty at Canberra's Australian National University.<Node id="731"/>
<Node id="732"/>"But with appropriate investment by government and investment bodies we could be in production in three or four years competing vigorously against diesel fuels."<Node id="893"/>
<Node id="894"/>The potential application for the new system was widespread, but it was envisaged that those areas not covered by the electricity grid, which were reliant on the transportation of diesel for their generators, would benefit most.<Node id="1122"/>
<Node id="1123"/>Other than the initial cost of the new solar system there would ideally be no need for any further financial outlay, particularly since there were no moving parts and no need for maintenance, Blakers said.<Node id="1328"/>
<Node id="1329"/>The new "epilift" process allowed the cheap production of the most expensive component of solar cells, the silicon wafers.<Node id="1451"/>
<Node id="1452"/>"Until now, the silicon wafers used by the solar industry have been made in a multi-step process that wastes around 90 percent of the expensive raw silicon," Blakers said.<Node id="1623"/>
<Node id="1624"/>With the old method, the silicon is decomposed into toxic and corrosive gases which are then condensed and resmelted into large blocks of pure silicon. Thin wafers are then cut off for cell production.<Node id="1825"/>
<Node id="1826"/>This expensive process accounts for half the cost of the finished solar cell, about A$4 - A$5 (US$3 - US$3.70) per watt.<Node id="1946"/>
<Node id="1947"/>The epilift technique grows each cell individually in a single step, employing a reusable silicon template and so is more efficient and more cost effective in the long term.<Node id="2120"/>
<Node id="2121"/>Laboratory trials of templates showed them to have a long reusable life and the group's business manager, Ulrich Theden, told Reuters they would only be vulnerable to direct damage through carelessness.<Node id="2323"/>
<Node id="2324"/>The epilift invention was now patent-protected and Theden said he would seek financial support from industries to continue research.<Node id="2456"/>
<Node id="2457"/>The response from companies approached, including the Broken Hill Pty Co Ltd, has been cautious ao far.<Node id="2560"/>
<Node id="2561"/>"In Australia, it is almost impossible to get any research money without industry support," Theden said.<Node id="2665"/>
<Node id="2666"/>"That's our biggest problem. To take our development to the next phase we would probably need A$1 - A$2 million a year for the next three or four years.<Node id="2818"/>
<Node id="2819"/>"With that money we would have a convicing product which we could hand over to industry to take into production."<Node id="2932"/>
<Node id="2933"/>(A$1 = US$0.74)<Node id="2948"/>
